<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Prudential rises 16% despite fall from UK life
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prudential Corporation, the UK's largest life insurer, reported a 16 per
cent rise to Pounds 280m in first-half pre-tax profits, but profits from the
UK life business fell.
The drop in profits from the UK long-term business, from Pounds 139m to
132m, reflected a decline in sales of insurance products and the cost to
shareholders of financing new unit-linked business.
It also took account of provision for potential reductions in bonuses on its
with-profits policies which are not set until the year-end in March.
Prudential and other insurers have cut bonus rates in line with lower
investment returns in recent years.
Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive, expected UK sales to be subdued in the
second half, but said that in the longer term the need for savings and
protection products should mean substantial demand.
The interim dividend was raised 9 per cent to 4.9p (4.5p).
Commenting on factors behind the uncertainty and caution among customers, Mr
Newmarch highlighted two areas of regulatory activity. The first was the
report from City regulators on compensating customers who have suffered from
poor advice to transfer out of occupational pension schemes, which is due
next month. The second means that from the start of next year life insurers
have to volunteer more information to customers about policies and charges.
Prudential's pension transfer sales are also being informally investigated
by Lautro, the regulator for the life insurance industry. The inquiry began
in April, and could last another couple of months. Prudential said it has
acted properly on pension transfers and has always conducted its sales
activities well within regulatory rules.
Pre-tax profits from Jackson National Life, Prudential's US subsidiary, rose
to Pounds 36m (Pounds 31m), while total profits were also helped by Pounds
17m from other international business, compared with a Pounds 6m loss last
year.
This profit included Pounds 5m for the sale of Prudential's Irish subsidiary
to the Irish Permanent Building Society.
Pre-tax profits from Prudential's general insurance businesses - UK domestic
and motor insurance and Mercantile and General Reinsurance - were sharply
increased to Pounds 53m (Pounds 18m).
Shareholders' other income fell to Pounds 32m from Pounds 53m as a result of
lower investment returns and a rise in corporate spending.
</TEXT>
