<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Observer: Tactical retreat
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Sounds as if one very important person is going to be missing from today's
junkets following the loan-signing in Warsaw of Poland's debt reduction deal
 -and it is not Citibank's Bill Rhodes. Polish president Lech Walesa has
cried off, citing a previous engagement in Poznan where he is due to fire
the closing shot in the first ever Nato manoeuvres on Polish soil.
Some western bankers are miffed since the president's diary seems remarkably
empty today. He's not due on parade in Poznan till tomorrow. Could it be
that Walesa is playing safe and distancing himself from a deal which could
turn out to be a mite too generous to the banks? Much more likely is that he
is desperate to get Poland into Nato and doesn't want to do anything to
upset the Nato high command.
Bankers are much more expendable.
</TEXT>
