<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is a lot of ambulance chasing on television today: 999 Lifesavers at
8.00 on BBC1 is followed by Blues And Twos on ITV at 8.30. And in case you
still feel deprived of material about the emergency services, in Critical
Eye, on Channel 4 (9.00), policewomen speak their minds about 'the gender
war behind the thin blue line' and Inside Story is about a police squad
hunting for stolen cars (10.00 BBC1). Radio 4 offers an enticing evening.
The Document series returns with a programme about 'The Voice Of Britain',
described as 'Goebbels-style broadcasts' to Egypt at the time of the Suez
fiasco (7.20). That is followed by Entente Cordiale in which Sir Charles
Powell, foreign affairs adviser to Margaret Thatcher, examines relations
between the UK and France (8.00). In Classic Storylines PD James, famous for
her own whodunnits, discusses
the book often credited with being the first detective story: The Moonstone
by Wilkie Collins (8.30). A new six-part drama series starring Donald
Pleasence begins at 11.00:
21st Century Blues, was written by Steve Walker, who is best known for the
children's series The Animals Of Farthing Wood.
