<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / TUC offers Ucatt cash support: Guarantee of Pounds 250,000
underlines determination to save construction union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Trades Union Congress has privately promised a Pounds 250,000 guarantee
to underwrite Ucatt, Britain's biggest construction union, as it prepares a
tough rescue plan aimed at achieving financial viability by the end of next
year.
This unprecedented decision underlines the TUC leadership's determination to
ensure that the union is saved from the threat of financial collapse. It
follows the TUC general council's decision to suspend Ucatt's Pounds 180,000
annual TUC subscription to enable the union to send delegates to last week's
congress.
The union expects to return to financial balance and believes it will not
need to make use of the TUC guarantee to Unity Trust Bank.
Ucatt officials led by Mr George Brumwell, the general secretary, yesterday
met HW Fisher, the union's accountants, and Unity Trust to discuss details
of the rationalisation programme which it is hoped can be finalised and
approved by the middle of next month.
The bank is preparing to provide further financial assistance to Ucatt -
possibly in the form of a loan - on top of the Pounds 1.428m overdraft
facility it has been providing on condition that agreement can be reached on
cuts to bring the union's finances into balance.
The union is using its many properties as collateral to the bank, which in
reality is ultimately responsible for monitoring Ucatt's finances on a
day-to-day basis.
Mr Brumwell said yesterday: 'The bank has continued to support us and it has
kept a tight rein on our current expenditure, but we have managed within the
overdraft facility.'
He emphasised that his executive was giving full backing to the new rescue
plan. 'We are increasingly confident we can get the union back into line,'
he said.
A rescue plan drawn up by the union and its accountants last year was found
to have taken too optimistic a view of membership income. Instead of rising
after two years of decline it has fallen by about Pounds 500,000 this year,
about 10 per cent of annual income.
The union's members are about to be balloted on a proposal that the union
become an autonomous trade group of the TGWU general union from next
January. Delegates at Ucatt's conference this summer voted in support of
joining the TGWU by only 32 to 30, but Mr Brumwell said he was 'very
confident' that the proposal would be approved by members.
He said this would make no difference to Ucatt's need to bring expenditure
into line with income. It has to meet interest and bank charges of about
Pounds 4,000 a week.
The main problem has been to ensure that it can establish financial support
to meet the cost of staff redundancies and other measures involved in the
planned rationalisation.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
