<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Ashdown plan aims to dull Labour's rising star
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Paddy Ashdown yesterday unveiled his strategy to take the Liberal
Democrats out of the shadow of Mr Tony Blair's Labour party by staking out a
distinctive political agenda for the next general election.
In a personal political manifesto designed to provide 'signposts' for his
party, Mr Ashdown insisted that Mr Blair's election as Labour leader would
strengthen rather than weaken the Liberal Democrats' electoral appeal.
Welcoming the decision of Mr Blair and his fellow Labour modernisers 'to
copy' many Liberal Democrat themes, Mr Ashdown said that the latest
upheavals in British politics could only benefit a third party committed to
change.
But he refused to drop the official party line - privately dismissed by many
of its senior figures - that the Liberal Democrats might co-operate with the
Conservatives after an inconclusive general election.
Mr Ashdown's policy statement, which will provide the focus for political
debate at next week's annual conference in Brighton, casts the Liberal
Democrats as the party best able to manage change in a rapidly changing
world.
Setting out the central planks of policy, Mr Ashdown said that the party had
to take as its starting point the acceptance of a market-based,
enterprise-driven economy, to enable Britain to compete in the global
economy.
It should also sketch out policies which involved building on, rather than
dismantling, the government's reforms of public services. Above all it
should focus on making the services democratic and accountable.
Mr Ashdown said the party should widen its traditional commitment to
constitutional reform by embracing new forms of democracy, including using
national and local consultative referenda to 'reconnect people with
politics'.
The policy statement, Making Change Our Ally, says that Britain must also
accept a pivotal role in Europe with a clear commitment to build a
democratic federal structure. On the wider international stage Britain
should play a leading role in reform of the United Nations to create the new
world order promised - but not delivered - by the end of the cold war.
</TEXT>
