<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Ministers warned on mortgage help
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was yesterday warned not to cut mortgage-interest subsidies
to people on benefits before the private sector can provide alternative
cover.
Amid signs that ministers plan to reduce mortgage interest relief in the
Budget, the social security advisory committee, which advises the government
on the welfare state, said people with big mortgages were already being
forced to take out insurance to cover interest payments.
It noted that the government had recently lowered the upper limit for a
mortgage on which it would pay interest relief to Pounds 125,000. But it
warned that the availability of insurance cover was 'variable' and that
further cuts would bring hardship to unemployed homeowners.
The committee said that insurance groups could be encouraged to look at
mortgage-interest cover in a number of ways. It said: 'One possible solution
might be for the mortgage lenders to adopt a pooled-risk approach to
unemployment and insure themselves against an individual being unable to pay
them.'
This would spread the risk evenly and ensure that no company was heavily
penalised.
It also called on the government to signal any intention to cut mortgage
relief well in advance. This would encourage homeowners and insurance
companies to make decisions on replacing state provision.
State Benefits and Private Provision. Social Security Advisory Committee.
New Court, 48 Carey St, London WC2.
</TEXT>
