<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Fresh law on animal transport planned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, yesterday outlined plans for
tough measures to improve the treatment of live animals on long journeys in
the hope of defusing the row between ferry companies and farmers over the
lucrative export trade.
But ferry companies - several of which have already implemented a ban on
transporting live animals after a public outcry - appeared unimpressed,
saying that they would maintain their bans.
The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals criticised the
new code, because it is applicable only in the UK and does not cover further
travel in the European Union. It questioned the ability of the UK
authorities to enforce the code and expressed disappointment that it did not
contain a maximum journey time of eight hours for animals bound for
slaughter.
Stena Sealink said its ban on carrying live animals would stay until a code
was drawn up that was acceptable to the RSPCA. Peninsular and Oriental,
which carries the bulk of live animal exports, said it was still committed
to banning the traffic from October 1.
Farmers hope that the ferry companies will rethink their objections to the
new code during the consultation period until October 18. Mr Waldegrave
urged ferry companies to act as if the code was already in place.
He said: 'This is an important initiative. In the absence of agreed and
enforceable EU measures, I shall be amending the law to give teeth to the
enforcement of best practice already required by our national controls.'
The code would introduce a new criminal offence for hauliers falsifying
journey plans. The measures would compel hauliers to fill in a standard
journey plan for all trips over 15 hours. Plans for departure, arrival times
and staging posts would have to be approved by a government vet.
Mr Waldegrave said that he recognised the need to toughen legislation at a
European level, but the measures in the code would give the government far
greater power to stop malpractice in Britain.
Farmers groups have warned that they stand to lose up to Pounds 200m a year
if the ferry companies' bans are maintained.
</TEXT>
