<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / WH Smith backs net book deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WH Smith, the UK's biggest bookseller, has decided to put its weight behind
the defence of the net book agreement as long as the main publishers do the
same.
The company, which has 23 per cent of the market through its main retail
outlets and the more specialist Waterstone chain, wants to preserve the NBA
in the interests of maintaining an orderly market in the publishing of new
books.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of Fair Trading, has asked the
Restrictive Practices Court to look again at the agreement which allows
publishers to set the retail prices of most books.
The last time the court looked at the issue in 1964 it concluded that
without the agreement fewer titles would be published, a narrower range of
titles would be available in bookshops and some independent bookshops might
go out of business.
The Publishers Association will decide later this month whether it will
defend the agreement in the Restrictive Practices Court - a long process
that could cost pub-lishers and retailers as much as Pounds 1m according to
some estimates.
There are growing signs that a majority of the council of the Publishers
Association will come out in favour of retaining the NBA. The question then
will become whether they are prepared to meet the cost of defending it in
court.
Earlier this month Sir Malcolm Field, managing director of WH Smith, spelt
out the implications of ending the NBA at a meeting of senior publishers in
London.
He said: 'The NBA is, and always has been, a publishers' agreement. If the
publishers want to retain it, then we expect them to defend it. As a group
we will support them. But we will not shoulder the burden ourselves.' If the
NBA went, they would have to 'take an axe to the slower-moving titles'.
Sir Malcolm predicted that the end of the NBA would result in the serious
book buyer subsidising discounts at the popular end of the market.
</TEXT>
