<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / New consortium sets its sights on Channel 5
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An international consortium, believed to include three big UK corporations
with no significant broadcasting interests, is to bid for the new Channel 5
television licence.
The group is led by CanWest Global Communications, a Canadian broadcasting
group with interests in New Zealand, Australia and Chile. It declined to
name its partners for the Channel 5 bid.
At the same time Virgin Communications, part of Mr Richard Branson's Virgin
Group, has appointed Mr Jeremy Fox, president of Channel 9 Australia, to
develop Virgin's broadcast interests, including a possible bid for Channel
5.
Mr Fox will stay as president of Channel 9, the international arm of Mr
Kerry Packer's television interests. He said: 'The plan is to put the Virgin
style on television to appeal to an audience that knows the Virgin brand.'
The growing interest in Channel 5 comes as the Independent Television
Commission meets today to decide whether to advertise a licence for the
channel. All the signs are that it will approved the new channel, and could
advertise the franchise by early November.
The channel would require the retuning of existing video recorders and new
aerials in some areas but is seen as one of the last broadcasting
opportunities with existing technology in a big European market.
Others who have expressed interest include NBC, the US network broadcaster,
Yorkshire-Tyne Tees, the ITV company, and a consortium of Time Warner,
Pearson - which owns the Financial Times - and MAI, the company that
controls Meridian Broadcasting.
Mr Stephen Castell, a communications consultant, intends to bid to use the
channel capacity for digital television services.
The big issue is the range the channel will have. The original frequency
plan envisaged that Channel 5 could reach about 75 per cent of the
population. The government, heavily influenced by Mr Michael Heseltine, the
trade and industry secretary, decided to set some of the frequencies aside
for the future development of digital terrestrial television.
As a result little more than 53 per cent of the country would be sure of
receiving Channel 5, although the ITC is already seeking international
permission to use new frequencies. A final reach of more than 60 per cent is
likely and there is a theoretical possibility that 70 per cent could
eventually receive the new channel.
The CanWest bid for the channel is being co-ordinated by Media Ventures
International, which bid successfully for the UK's third national commercial
radio licence with UK Talk Radio. CanWest is an investor in the station.
Media Ventures also bid successfully with Associated Newspapers for the ITV
teletext licence.
</TEXT>
