<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Baseball season brought to an end
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last night Americans, or at least those who care about what really matters,
were glumly facing the fact that next month will be like no peacetime
October in 90 years. The rest of the baseball season, including the
climactic World Series championship, was cancelled.
After 34 days of a strike by the players, the inevitably curtain was finally
rung down by Mr Bud Selig, who is both acting commissioner of baseball and
owner of the Milwaukee Brewers team. 'This is a sad day,' he said.
Mr Mario Cuomo, the governor of New York and once a promising young
professional himself, probably expressed national emotions more accurately,
if neutrally. 'It was a wicked thing to do; a really wicked thing,' he
lamented over the loss of what had promised to be a record-breaking season
for several players (and possibly a championship one for the New York
Yankees).
Mr Selig naturally blamed the players, who walked out on August 12 after
complex, protracted negotiations over a new contract broke down. The strike,
he said, 'leaves us with no choice'. Actually, the owners of two clubs, the
Baltimore Orioles and the Cincinnati Reds, voted against turning off the
lights, but there was no sign they would barnstorm the nation and play each
other exclusively for the next month.
This was baseball's eighth industrial dispute in the last 22 years.
The technical sticking point was the players' refusal to accept the owners'
proposal of a cap on team salaries, designed to distribute revenues more
evenly among the rich and poor clubs.
But it would be wrong to ascribe the breakdown to the greed of the players
(minimum salary Dollars 109,000 - Pounds 70,000 - a year, maximum individual
contract Dollars 31,500 a game). The owners themselves have failed to
address revenue-sharing for years and have consistently refused to open
their books to the public or the players' union.
Since the walk-out, it has been the players who have made all the
negotiating proposals and who contended last night that the owners' action
was premature.
It is far from clear that there will be a next season. Spring training
normally resumes late in February. Both sides have some hard thinking to do
over the winter.
</TEXT>
