<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Dutch study hits at Unilever detergent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RODERICK ORAM, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unilever's new laundry detergent was criticised yesterday by the Dutch
consumers' association, which concluded after tests that 'the damage' the
detergent did to some clothes was 'too great'.
Unilever rejected the report, which is likely to intensify the 'Soap War'
raging between the Anglo-Dutch group and Procter and Gamble since Unilever
launched the power detergents this summer. P&amp;G is highly critical of the
detergents' alleged effect on clothes.
Omo Power, sold as Persil Power in the UK, was as effective at washing
clothes 'as any other good washing powder and bleach,' the Dutch association
said. But some fabrics, particularly coloured cotton, had been 'damaged' in
the test.
'The data is partial and being used in a very emotive way,' Unilever said.
It criticised the association for making 'sweeping statements' comparing Omo
Power to other detergents when, it said, it had run tests against only one
other unnamed detergent.
It said the association had also failed to judge the effect on clothes and
the alleged lessening of tensile strength, which enables a garment to resume
its shape after being stretched, against textile industry standards.
It is understood Unilever has seen the full data from the Dutch
association's tests and found them comparable to data from six independent
test institutes it commissioned to study the detergent. The six institutes
found the effect the detergent had on clothes was acceptable and fell within
textile industry standards.
In the UK, the Consumers' Association is conducting its own tests on Persil
Power but results will not be ready before mid-December. Marks &amp; Spencer,
also conducting tests, said it did not know when they would be completed.
'We continue to monitor the level of returned clothes but there's nothing
that causes immediate concern.'
Unilever said the impact of the Dutch report would be limited; sales of all
products in the Omo brand had not been harmed. Albert Heijn, the Dutch
supermarket chain, said: 'We see no reason to take it out of our shops. We
will wait to see what consumers do.' P&amp;G welcomed the report. 'This cannot
come as any surprise in light of the evidence that had already emerged,'
said Mr David Veitch, P&amp;G's European vice-president of communications.
</TEXT>
