<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / IMF warned of 'ruin' over loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Monetary Fund could face ruin unless it starts to apply
its normal credit conditions for loans to former east bloc communist
countries, Swiss National Bank president Markus Lusser said yesterday. The
ratio of debt to exports in the so-called transition countries was already
higher than that in the developing nations, except for sub-Saharan African
states, he said. The IMF must insist the transition countries quickly meet
the normal conditions set for its loans, as further protracted waiving of
its so-called 'conditionality' would be too risky. 'The currency reserves of
IMF member countries would be endangered. Their credibility would suffer
damage. The catalytic effect would be lost,' he said in remarks prepared for
a Swiss Christian Democratic People's Party meeting in Zug. 'The transition
would run the risk of ending in the financial and moral ruin of the IMF.' Mr
Lusser said the IMF's financial aid, particularly to former communist
countries, would increase massively in the next few years.
</TEXT>
