<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Phone ruling promises savings on US-UK calls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The cost of transatlantic phone calls is set to fall sharply with a ruling
by US regulators, expected next week, opening the way to greater competition
on the UK-US route.
The ruling will allow a new form of competition, called international simple
resale. It will have far-reaching implications for the cartel involving
international phone companies, which keeps cross-border prices artificially
high.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC), the US regulatory authority, is
expected to rule that the UK's telecoms market is sufficiently open to US
operators to justify the new form of competition. The UK will make a
reciprocal declaration, after which the regime can operate.
Telecoms companies will then be able to resell to their customers capacity
leased from the main transatlantic carriers at a discount to present
tariffs, and connect the calls into the public networks in both countries.
Until now, the telecoms companies have not been allowed to utilise the
public networks on both sides of the Atlantic, restricting their market
mainly to the large corporate sector. The operators will now be able to
reach smaller businesses and residential customers.
The US and the UK have competitive telecoms regimes, with well-established
domestic rivals to British Telecommunications, the former UK monopoly
operator, and to American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, which had a near monopoly
in the US market until its break-up in 1984. Several large US phone
companies have gained licences to operate in the UK since the abolition of
the BT/Mercury duopoly in 1991, with AT&amp;T itself granted a draft licence in
July. UK operators are also active in the US.
AT&amp;T fought strongly against the latest ruling by the FCC. Yesterday it
claimed that BT was keeping prices artificially high by refusing to agree to
its plan for a cut of nearly two-thirds in the rate which BT and AT&amp;T pay
each other for connecting international calls.
Transatlantic phone prices have already fallen sharply, with BT's UK-US
prices down more than a third in three years.
However, analysts believe there is large scope for further cuts. Industry
estimates suggest that it costs resale operators little more than 7p a
minute in direct network charges to deliver a US-UK call, yet the daytime
prices charged by BT and AT&amp;T average nearly 45p a minute.
The US accounts for about a fifth of BT's international traffic, while the
UK is the third-largest destination for outgoing calls from the US.
BT conceded yesterday that there was 'some room' for splitting the
difference between leased-line rates and existing prices, but said that if,
as expected, it gained the necessary regulatory consents, it would join the
resale market through its joint venture with MCI, the second-largest US
carrier.
Mr Thomas Luciano, AT&amp;T's director of international settlements, said: 'The
industry is beginning to pull apart from a system of co-operation between
carriers, which will open things up in a new way.'
Lex, Page 20
Speculation mounts on Sprint mobile deal, Page 27
</TEXT>
