<HEADLINE>
FT  15 SEP 94 / Air France pilots to strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Pilots at Air France are to strike tomorrow and Saturday after talks on
productivity broke down. The strike is a setback for Mr Christian Blanc, Air
France's chairman, who wants to raise productivity by 30 per cent by 1997 as
part of a rescue package. Last year, the ailing state-owned carrier suffered
losses of FFr8.48bn (Pounds 1.02bn). The SNPL pilots' union opposes plans to
cut flight bonuses while Mr Blanc claims the pilots' counter-proposals on
productivity would increase average pay by about 10 per cent. 'No company,
even the most flourishing can allow that today, and Air France is not
flourishing,' he said in a letter to the union. Air France said it could
guarantee about a third of medium-range international flights tomorrow and
Saturday and hopes to run more long-range flights.
