<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Tame CPI rise gives Dow
renewed heart
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks improved yesterday as a tame reading on consumer price inflation
brought some encouragement to a depressed bond market, writes Frank McGurty
in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 19.52 firmer at 3,879.86, while
the more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 1.30 at 467.51.
Advancing issues outpaced declines on the Big Board by a slim margin
following volume of 295.7m shares.
In the secondary markets, the American SE composite was 1.75 better at
456.81 and the Nasdaq composite forged 5.82 ahead to 765.83.
A two-session bout of selling, triggered by news of a sharp increase in
producer prices, came to an end yesterday morning. Before the market opened,
the Labor Department had revealed a 0.3 per cent rise in the August consumer
price index, a figure that compared favourably with the consensus forecast.
Amid the relief, investors largely ignored contradictory evidence in a
regional manufacturing survey. The Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta said the
prices-paid component of its monthly survey of business conditions showed a
moderate upturn.
In spite of that unfavourable news, analysts said the more benign reading on
inflation in the consumer sector would allow the Federal Reserve to wait
until November before lifting short-term interest rates again.
That scenario had seemed less credible in the aftermath of last week's
report on producer prices.
The more positive outlook yesterday enabled bonds to finish with decent
gains, but only after the market reversed direction several times. By
comparison, equities were steadfast. The early gains eroded a bit near
midday, but the market regained its stride later.
Among the Dow industrials, raw material suppliers - which benefit from the
accelerating trend in producer prices - led the way. Alcoa closed Dollars 1
3/8 stronger at Dollars 84 and International Paper climbed Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 74 1/2 .
Elsewhere in the robust paper and pulp sector, Georgia Pacific gained
Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 73 and Champion International added Dollars 1 1/4
at Dollars 36 5/8 .
Market bellwether stock IBM set the positive tone among technology issues,
moving forward Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 69 1/4 .
Semiconductor issues showed some sparkle following the release of the August
book-to-bill ratio, a keenly watched indicator of the industry's future
performance. A surpris-
ingly strong reading sent Micron Technology Dollars  7/8 higher to Dollars
39 7/8 and Texas Instruments up Dollars 1 to Dollars 75 1/2 .
The session propelled two relative unknowns into the New York SE's most
active list. Western Company of North America, an oil services concern,
jumped Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 16 3/4 after BJ Services announced its
interest in acquiring the company. BJ said it was appealing directly to
Western's shareholders after the rejection of its unsolicited Dollars 450m
offer, worth Dollars 18.50 a share.
Meanwhile, EMC appreciated Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 18 1/2 in unusually
brisk trading of 3.1m shares. The activity reflected a positive reaction by
analysts to the company's announcement that it was developing storage
applications for 'video on demand' services.
Mexico
Equity prices ended just slightly higher after losing their earlier Wall
Street generated steam.
The IPC index of the 37 most traded stocks was 4.55 points up on balance at
2,713.34 after touching 2,725.25.
Analysts said the Mexican market was basically in a period of consolidation
while awaiting news of earnings reports, the annual anti-inflation pact
between government, business and labour - due to be renewed shortly - and
incoming President Ernesto Zedillo's new cabinet.
</TEXT>
<XX>
