<DATE>940914
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / International Company News: KKR offer displays its passion
for complexity - The Borden bid has left observers scratching their heads on
who stands to gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For connoisseurs of 1980s financial engineering, Monday's Dollars 2bn bid by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts for Borden, the US food group, brings a nostalgic
tear to the eye.
It evokes the high-water mark of 1980s deal-making - KKR's Dollars 26bn
purchase of RJR Nabisco, the large food and tobacco group.
Five years on, KKR - still the most formidable of the Wall Street buy-out
firms - proposes to pay for Borden not with ready money, but with RJR
shares.
It is a reminder of KKR's passion for complexity. In a deal described by one
Wall Street analyst - not without admiration - as 'pure smoke and mirrors',
observers are left scratching their heads on who stands to gain. KKR
evidently thinks it does. But what about Borden's shareholders, or RJR's?
For the average Borden shareholder, KKR's Dollars 14.25 a share offer is
nothing to shout about.
A year ago the stock stood at more than Dollars 19; two years ago it was
double that. And Dollars 2bn is a pitiful price for a leading US food
company with sales of Dollars 5.5bn. Campbell Soup, a decently profitable
food company which until recently had sales smaller than Borden's, has a
market value of about Dollars 10bn.
However, no one is betting on a better offer coming along. Borden is in a
mess. Its sales have dropped every year in the past five. In the past two
years, it has incurred large losses, mostly because of costly restructuring
plans which the company admits have proved ineffectual. A year ago it halved
its dividend, then halved it again. In spite of sharp cuts in capital
spending and inventories, cash flow has continued to dwindle. Until KKR came
along, Borden seemed to be heading for the rocks.
The mistakes which brought the company to this situation are sadly familiar.
In the second half of the 1980s, Borden embarked on an ambitious and
badly-managed series of acquisitions. As a result, it neglected its basic
business. For example, Borden has been in the dairy business for 140 years,
and is America's biggest dairy company. Last year its dairy division lost
about Dollars 35m on turnover of about Dollars 1.5bn.
The obvious question is what the financial jugglers of KKR can do to set
this right.
There are some simple answers. If the dairy business, for example, cannot be
sold, KKR can afford to close it down, whereas Borden could not.
A large part of Borden has nothing to do with food. It is the world's
biggest maker of wallpaper and owns Crown in the UK. The non-food businesses
made Dollars 172m of operating profit on sales of Dollars 1.8bn last year,
while food made only Dollars 23m on sales of Dollars 3.7bn.
Since those businesses generate high levels of cash, Borden could ill afford
to sell them. But KKR has deeper pockets, and could doubtless make a profit
on disposals.
The rest of KKR's calculations are murkier. KKR is apparently paying Dollars
2bn for the whole of Borden, payment being in the form of about half KKR's
remaining stake in RJR shares. But as soon as the deal is complete, RJR has
undertaken to buy 20 per cent of Borden from KKR, at a cost of Dollars 500m
 -again, payment being in RJR shares.
KKR's net payment for control of Borden is therefore Dollars 1.5bn. More
fundamentally, KKR is in effect liquidating half its remaining equity stake
in RJR - which has proved a rather dubious investment - so that it can back
another horse in the form of Borden. In the process, analysts reckon, it may
crystallise a useful tax loss.
More important, RJR as a recovery story may be played out. Its food profits
have risen sharply in the past three years, and may not have much further to
go. Tobacco, meanwhile, is under fire from US legislators and litigants as
never before.
Borden, by contrast, is a pure recovery play. If things came right, the
results could be spectacular.
Meanwhile, what about RJR's shareholders?
KKR, it must be recalled, does not technically control RJR: its equity
holding is only 35 per cent, and is due to fall to half that. But the
suspicion must be that KKR calls the shots.
It is slightly worrying that the deal envisages the sale of assets by Borden
to RJR. Even at the outset, RJR shareholders suffer dilution through the
issue of Dollars 500m of new RJR stock to buy 20 per cent of Borden, and RJR
has the option to buy a further 10 per cent.
On the other hand, there is plainly some scope for putting bits of the two
companies together.
For example, Borden owns the second biggest snack food business in the US.
Like the dairy business, it loses money. But this is a business RJR
understands. It owns Planters peanuts, and its Nabisco subsidiary is
America's biggest biscuit maker, with the distribution muscle to go with it.
In the end, one simple consideration may outweigh all that.
KKR has owned and controlled RJR for five years. It knows and understands
the business like no one else. For outside shareholders, this raises one
simple question. If KKR wants out, why would anyone else want to stay
behind?
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Kohlberg Kravis Roberts and Co.
    RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.
    Borden Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6799 Investors, NEC.
    P2026 Fluid Milk.
    P2111 Cigarettes.
    P2099 Food Preparations, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Mergers &amp; acquisitions.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
