<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / UK Company News: Kenya shilling boosts James Finlay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Strength of the Kenya shilling lay behind a 30 per cent rise in pre-tax
profits at James Finlay, the overseas trading and financial services group,
in the first half of 1994.
Profits rose to Pounds 4.94m (Pounds 3.8m) after an exchange gain this time
of Pounds 646,000, against losses last of Pounds 1.32m. Turnover advanced to
Pounds 82m (Pounds 76.3m).
Mr Richard Capper, deputy chairman, expected the Kenyan tea crop to be about
20m kg, some 2m kg down on the previous first half. This led to operating
profits from plantations (excluding Bangladesh, where the tea is not picked
until late in the first half) falling to Pounds 2.46m (Pounds 2.57m).
Lower tea trading was offset by reduced losses at Finlay Industries in the
US, which makes tractors and lawn mowers and the trading, manufacturing and
merchanting division saw lower profits of Pounds 1.21m (Pounds 1.55m).
A bright spot was the confectionery and beverage manufacturing side, where
profits advanced to Pounds 1.77m (Pounds 1.12m) on the back of greater
volumes at Paynes and a lower interest bill.
Losses on the oil and gas side fell to Pounds 157,000 (Pounds 418,000) and
the group took a provision of Pounds 2.9m against the discontinuance of
these operations by the end of the year. Mr Capper said it was 'such a small
part of the Finlay empire' and had not been a very good investment.
The provision was offset by a profit of Pounds 3.2m from the disposal of the
18 per cent stake in Rockall Scotia Resources.
Mr Capper said that the 31 per cent tax charge was likely to rise between 40
and 45 per cent for the year, against 71 per cent last time.
Earnings increased to 3.3p (1p) per share and the interim dividend is held
at 2p.
</TEXT>
