<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The last in the Channel 4 series Witness seeks to discover how Sascha
Anderson, known as a leading light in the dissident movement in East Germany
before the fall of the Berlin Wall, came to be one of the top informers for
the secret police. Among those he reported to the Stasi were his own wife
and the Swedish journalist Bjorn Cederberg. Here Cederberg interviews
Anderson's betrayed friends and tracks down the man himself (9.00). The
first of a new series of Video Diaries is made by a schizophrenic named
Sharon who was abandoned at birth, brought up in a foster home, took an
overdose at 13, but is now married (to another schizophrenic) and living in
a flat in Manchester (9.30 BBC2). Last week's opening episode of BBC1's
drama series about dustmen, Common As Muck, showed distinct promise: drama,
comedy, character and dialogue all well above average. The second episode
today should show whether this was a flash in the pan (10.00). ITV screens a
two-hour recording of the Donmar Warehouse production of Cabaret with Jane
Horrocks as Sally Bowles (10.40).
