<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Regulators criticised over competition role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Utility regulators concentrate too much on promoting competition and not
enough on the strategic development of the industries they regulate, a
think-tank close to the Labour party said yesterday.
The report from the Institute for Public Policy Research, says regulation
should aim to raise the international competitiveness of UK utilities and
their suppliers.
The government should set industrial policy objectives for each sector,
which the regulators should implement. At present they are inventing
industrial policies for the utilities they regulate, it says.
The report calls for individual industry regulators to be replaced by four
regulatory commissions covering energy, communications, transport and water.
The commissions should include representatives of stakeholders in the
industries such as customers, suppliers and employees.
They should operate much more openly, with accountability to parliament
through a new select committee.
Mr David Souter, head of research at the NCU telecommunications union and
one of the authors of the report, said yesterday that the promotion of
competition by regulators was a form of 'industrial policy by default'. He
called for an 'industrial policy by design' for utilities that affected the
quality of life of every citizen and provided the infrastructure on which
businesses depended.
He said: 'Competition won't deliver important public policy objectives such
as energy-efficiency and regional fairness.' A less adversarial relationship
was needed between regulators and the utilities.
Professor Michael Waterson of Warwick University, the other author, said
regulation by price-caps was reaching the end of its usefulness. It allowed
some utilities to pass on certain costs to the consumer, and was
inappropriate where companies were diversifying.
Regulating Our Utilities. IPPR, 30 Southampton Street, London WC2E 7RA.
Pounds 9.95.
Editorial comment, Page 19
</TEXT>
