<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Exchange may ease rules on Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange might soon relax its rules governing the listing of new
Lloyd's investment vehicles, according to professionals at the insurance
market. The change would make it possible for Lloyd's managing agents to
obtain a stock market listing for 'dedicated' funds, which would supply
capital exclusively to their own syndicates.
Lloyd's raised about Pounds 800m in capital last year from corporate
investors for the first time in its 300-year history. But at present all
corporate investment funds listed on the exchange are categorised as
investment trusts and do not need to show a three-year trading record.
Market sources suggest that the exchange is prepared to allow an immediate
listing for a dedicated vehicle if its syndicates have a three-year trading
record and the last three years' accounts have been signed off.
A financier in a corporate capital scheme said: 'There would appear to be
light at the end of the tunnel. There would appear to be an accommodation.'
Relaxation would be unlikely to trigger a surge of interest from investors.
Many Lloyd's investment trusts are trading at a discount to their net asset
value. But institutional investors in particular are unenthusiastic about
the market's prospects.
The market is widely expected to make a profit of about Pounds 800m to
Pounds 1bn for the 1993 underwriting year, the results for which will be
reported in 1996, bringing it into the black for the first time since 1987.
The chief executive of one agency, who has given up plans to raise dedicated
funds, said: 'We'd quite like a lot more capital but they are not queueing
up.'
Mr Peter Middleton, Lloyd's chief executive, said last month that the market
could raise between Pounds 125m and Pounds 250m in corporate capital for the
1995 underwriting year.
