<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Dairy court battle launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Dairy Trade Federation yesterday started moves to mount a High Court
challenge to the deregulation of the milk distribution industry in England
and Wales.
The industry body is seeking judicial review of the establishment of Milk
Marque, a voluntary farmers' co-operative to succeed the Milk Marketing
Board. It alleges that the new body will create an unregulated monopoly
which will force up the price of milk and other dairy products.
The federation said it hoped the action would lead to new safeguards for
consumers.
The government has agreed that the assets of the Milk Marketing Board, which
has been responsible for milk distribution for the past 60 years, should be
transferred to Milk Marque, and is anxious that it should come into being
without any further delay.
Mr Gavin Strang, Labour's agriculture spokesman, yesterday called on the
government to halt the deregulation scheme. He said it would inflict 'real
and unnecessary damage' on the industry.
He urged Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, to protect the
consumer and the industry from price increases and job losses, 'all of which
are a direct result of the government's own actions'.
