<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Getty plea on statue rejected
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A High Court judge yesterday ruled that Mr Stephen Dorrell, national
heritage secretary, did not act unfairly in allowing extra time for Pounds
7.6m to be raised to keep the sculpture The Three Graces in Britain.
Mr Justice Laws refused the California-based J Paul Getty Trust, which had
agreed to buy the statue, a judicial review of Mr Dorrell's decision.
The trust told the court sitting in Leeds that a fresh application would be
made to the Court of Appeal within seven days.
The Getty Trust had agreed to pay Pounds 7.6m for the Antonio Canova
sculpture. The government extended a deferral of a decision to grant an
export licence earlier this year to allow the Victoria and Albert Museum and
the National Galleries of Scotland to raise the money. On August 9 Mr
Dorrell allowed a further three months' delay.
The Getty Trust argued that Mr Dorrell had said the first delay of six
months was a final one and the delay should not have been extended, and that
Pounds 3.6m towards the purchase from the National Heritage Memorial Fund
was unlawful state aid under European Union rules.
The judge accepted the government's denial that it had assured the Getty
Museum in February that the six-month deferral would be final. He said Mr
Dorrell was entitled to give great weight to what he saw as the cultural
importance of the Graces, and he was reasonable to conclude that a British
offer was at that time within striking distance of matching that of the
Getty Trust.
The judge rejected the argument over state aid, as neither the V&amp;A nor the
National Galleries are commercial undertakings.
He awarded costs against the Getty Trust in respect of the case against the
secretary of state but said it should not pay the court costs of the
National Heritage Memorial Fund.
</TEXT>
