<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Sex bias payouts found to have risen sevenfold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Payouts in sexual discrimination cases have risen sevenfold since a European
Court of Justice ruling removed the statutory limit, an independent pay
analyst says today.
The equal opportunities review published by Industrial Relations Services
says that the decision has forced employers to take equal-opportunities
issues more seriously.
The report says that even when the awards made against the Ministry of
Defence over pregnancy dismissal cases are excluded the figures still show
that awards made by industrial tribunals in cases of unlawful discrimination
have risen 45 per cent.
The average compensation award over the 10 months before the European court
decision in November was Pounds 3,044. Since the decision the average has
risen to Pounds 21,785, mainly because of the MoD awards. Without the MoD
awards, however, the rise was still significant, increasing to Pounds 4,328.
Average awards for injury to feelings also rose from Pounds 1,371 before the
European court ruling to Pounds 1,796 afterwards.
Mr Gary Bowker, co-editor of the review, said: 'There is now a clear
financial incentive for employers to take equal treatment seriously and
import the principles of equality law into their personnel decisions.'
Taking the Cap Off Discrimination Awards - Equal Opportunities Review No.
57, September/October 1994. Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury
Place, London N5 1QP. By subscription.
