<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / London Underground signs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Piccadilly Circus, Leicester Square, Marble Arch. London Underground
believes there is money to be made from the name signs which adorn its
stations, Charles Batchelor writes.
Mr Mike Horne (above), London Underground commercial development manager,
displays some of the 10,000 redundant station signs that will be auctioned
on November 30 in what the company believes will be the biggest sale of its
kind.
Some of the signs date from the 1920s but others have fallen victim to more
recent station refurbishments. Some are battered veterans of life
underground while others have never been used and are in pristine condition.
So confident are London Underground and auctioneers Brooks of interest in
the collection of enamel, glass and aluminium signs that they have hired
Olympia, one of London's biggest exhibition halls, for the sale.
Mr Robert Brooks, chief executive, said: 'We have already been inundated
with calls from as far away as the US, Japan and Australia by people who had
got wind of the sale. We expect interest from rail enthusiasts, tourists,
and the owners of restaurants and theme parks. This is a chance to buy a
part of London's history.'
The sale will include some of the best-known station names on the Tube as
well as more prosaic indicators of the way to the Exit, the Ladies or the
Gentlemen.
The more popular and more unusual signs are expected to fetch several
hundred pounds each but even the less glamorous destinations such as Turnham
Green and Stamford Brook may attract interest from local residents. Football
enthusiasts may want to acquire signs to Arsenal or Wimbledon.
Mr Brooks said: 'People may want to own the sign of the station where they
first met their future husband or wife.'
Photograph: Tony Andrews
</TEXT>
