FT  14 SEP 94 / Mining survey finds that fewer than half of redundant miners
have found jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fewer than half of redundant miners questioned for a survey have found jobs
and those now working outside the industry have taken taken an average pay
cut of more than Pounds 70 a week, Michael Smith writes.
The survey by Coalfield Communities Campaign, an all-party association of
coalfield local authorities, found that 89 per cent of former miners were
worse off.
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, said the
report demonstrated the cost paid by miners for the government's failure to
back their industry.
A total of 878 former miners at five pits closed since October 1992
responded. This represented 30 per cent of questionnaires which were sent
out between December last year and April this year.
About 56 per cent had not found new work. Of those in work the largest
proportion were in factory or warehouse jobs.
