<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Inspectors attack 'narrow' work-based qualification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
New work-based qualifications concentrate too much on narrow practical
skills and provide insufficient knowledge and understanding about the job,
inspectors from the Further Education Funding Council said yesterday.
This criticism came in a report on the national vocational qualifications
introduced into colleges and workplaces over the past few years. The
council, whose responsibilities include ensuring the quality of further
education in England, also said that there was little evidence that these
qualifications were meeting their objective of rationalising vocational
qualifications.
In some colleges, they said, 'there has been an increase in the number of
awards. For example, in some vocational areas NVQs are now offered alongside
traditional qualifications'. More worrying for the government will be the
criticisms of the qualifications themselves.
The inspectors said there was evidence of widespread misunderstanding of the
aim of the National Council for Vocational Qualifications, which developed
the NVQs, that knowledge and understanding should be integral elements of
competence to do a job.
Some lecturers and assessors, as well as employers and a few employees, had
expressed concern about trainees' understanding of the principles underlying
competence.
A study commissioned by the inspectorate in brickwork, business
administration and hairdressing compared the new qualifications with those
they replaced. The overall impression gained from the study was that NVQ
trainees would be better fitted to carry out immediately the practical tasks
required in a particular job, but less able to appreciate the job in its
context and to react to changing circumstances.
Dr Terry Melia, the Further Education's Funding Council's chief inspector,
said more attention should be devoted to core skills and underpinning
knowledge, while employers should become more involved in training and
assessment in the workplace if the qualifications were to have credibility.
National Survey Report NVQs in the FE sector in England.
</TEXT>
<XX>
