<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Tory grassroots to press Clarke for tax cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rightwing Conservative MPs yesterday warned the chancellor that grassroots
members of the party wanted tax cuts soon, as Mr John Maples, party
vice-chairman, stressed that the Treasury had only ruled them out this year.
Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, said he thought there would be room
for tax cuts before the general election but also predicted further rises in
interest rates.
After the decision by the Treasury to rule out tax cuts this year Mr David
Shaw, vice-chairman of the Tory backbench finance committee, said a number
of his colleagues would be pressing the case for small reductions in
taxation.
He said: 'It should be fairly evident to government ministers and those in
parliament that the party out there, as well as people in the country at
large, want to see some sort of down-payment on tax cuts and want them to
start soon.'
Another rightwing backbencher said: 'Mr Kenneth Clarke (the chancellor)
would do well to think again. We need tax cuts now.'
While the chancellor remains confident that he will be able to face down any
protests from the right over his decision not to reduce taxes, senior
backbenchers made it clear that the party would expect them to follow a
period of sustained growth.
Sir Geoffrey Johnson-Smith, vice-chairman of the 1922 Committee of Tory MPs,
said: 'We have to get public expenditure under control first, which will
lead to a period of sustained growth.
'Then we will be in a strong position to cut taxes.'
Mr Lamont said: 'I think there will be room, given the improvement in our
finances, before the next election for some modest tax cuts.'
The chancellor had 'skilfully lowered expectations' by correctly indicating
that those cuts would not come this year.
He added: 'He has very wisely taken a medium-term view and taken steps that
will place the Conservative party in a very strong position in two years'
time.'
He urged backbench critics of the chancellor's stance to keep their nerve
and said the government's willingness to control inflation would enhance its
credibility.
Mr Lamont also predicted further interest rate rises - only 24 hours after
the Treasury announced a 0.5 per cent increase.
He told the BBC that he expected to see rates 'edging up' towards 7 per cent
in the next year.
His prediction is at odds with the comments of Mr Jeremy Hanley,
Conservative party chairman, who said he hoped there would be no further
increases in the cost of borrowing.
</TEXT>
