<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Charities' portfolio range set to widen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Charity Commissioners are considering widening the investment powers of
charities to allow the use of derivatives in managing charitable portfolios.
Derivatives are financial instruments, the value of which is based on an
underlying investment such as shares and bonds.
Mr Sanjay Sen, assistant commissioner, said the use of derivatives was one
aspect of a review on investment powers which was being undertaken by the
commissioners. They are likely to make their recommendations later this
year.
The review reflects the commissioners' policy of seeking to broaden the
investment powers of charities. Last month restrictions on investing
elsewhere in Europe were lifted.
At present the use of derivatives is confined to common investment funds,
which are pooled investment vehicles designed for charities. They work in
the same way as unit trusts but dividends can be reinvested gross.
The investable assets of charities, excluding property and cash, are
estimated at Pounds 25bn, but only about Pounds 4bn to Pounds 5bn is
invested in common investment funds.
The commissioners have consulted fund managers on the use of derivatives.
</TEXT>
