<BYLINE>
   By Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israeli foreign minister Shimon Peres and PLO head Yassir Arafat agreed
yesterday on ways to speed up donations to Palestinian self-rule projects
and to put the thorny issue of Jerusalem on one side for the time being,
agencies report from Oslo.
'We have the peace process back on track,' Mr Bjoern Tore Godal, Norwegian
foreign minister said.
The agreement, signed after a concert honouring the peace breakthrough a
year ago, was expected to put to rest bickering over the status of
Jerusalem, even though the city is never mentioned by name in the final
draft. In a 14-point document the PLO agreed to stick by the declaration of
principles under which Jerusalem's status would not be discussed for two
years.
Palestinian negotiators in Paris last week demanded to use part of the money
for health and education programmes in East Jerusalem. Israel objected,
saying any issue on Jerusalem was off limits until 1996, under the peace
accord. The talks then stalled.
