<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 94 / Forte fails to win control of Savoy but expands role:
Chairman announced in shake-up as company keeps independence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Rocco Forte won a role in the management of the Savoy hotel group
yesterday. But the prize of overall control - for which his family has
battled for 13 years - eluded him: the Savoy remains an independent company.
The board announced that the Savoy would have a new chairman in Sir Ewen
Fergusson, former British ambassador to France. He succeeds Sir Anthony
Tuke, who is retiring at the end of the year. The board said it would
appoint a new managing director to succeed Mr Giles Shepard, who resigned on
Monday. This is likely to be Mr Ramon Pajares, general manager of London's
Four Seasons hotel.
The board added that a chairman's committee would be set up to work with the
new managing director. It would include Sir Ewen; Mr Forte, who chairs the
Forte group; and Mr John Sinclair, who represents shareholding trusts
controlled by the family of Sir Hugh Wontner, Savoy president until his
death in 1992.
That is a success for Mr Forte, indicating acceptance that his group has a
legitimate interest in the Savoy's future. Forte owns 68 per cent of Savoy's
shares and 42 per cent of its votes. Nevertheless, Savoy loyalists such as
Sir Hugh and Mr Shepard had long regarded Forte as a cost-cutting group
unsuited to run such venerable properties as the Savoy, Claridge's and the
Connaught.
The Savoy announcement went on, however, to say: 'The board has been
informed that discussions between Forte and certain of the trusts which have
a significant interest in the share capital of the Savoy have terminated.'
That means that the trusts controlled by the Wontner family are no longer
thinking of aligning themselves with Forte to give the latter control. The
dual share structure set up by Sir Hugh in the 1950s to see off predators
such as Sir Charles Clore and Mr Harold Samuel, and which continues to
deprive Forte of overall control, remains in place.
The decisions followed months of acrimony and speculation. The Savoy board
gathered at 11.30 am to settle the group's future and by lunchtime had
finished after an apparently even-tempered gathering.
Forte, however, was putting a brave face on the outcome. It said it fully
associated itself with the words of Sir Anthony, who said: 'The board has a
common pur-pose which is to provide the highest-quality service for all our
customers at the same time as producing an adequate return for all our
shareholders.'
Under new management, the Savoy is likely to improve on its financial
performance of last year, when it made pre-tax profits of only Pounds
725,000 on turnover of Pounds 83.3m. It announces first-half 1994 profits
today. A better return might satisfy Forte.
'It's the end of the story,' one long-time participant in the struggle said
hopefully. On the other hand, it might prove difficult for Forte to abandon
an ambition of gaining full control.
Time is certainly on the Fortes' side. Mr Forte's father, Lord Forte, who
launched the takeover battle in 1981, is still going strong at the age of
85. Mr Forte is a youthful 49 - and his son Charles is not yet three.
Lex, Page 20
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                    THE BATTLE FOR THE SAVOY
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
1955: Savoy Hotel creates 'B' shares with weighted voting rig
      hts to bolster defences against takeovers.
1981: Forte launches hostile Pounds58m bid. It gains 68 per cent of
      shares but only 42 per cent of the vote.
1981-89: Forte campaigns to secure change in voting structure to
      enable it to obtain control of Savoy.
1989: Truce agreed. Forte appoints two directors to Savoy board;
      agrees not to increase its stake for five years. Campaign
      on voting structure continues.
1994: Mr Rocco Forte is appointed to Savoy's three-man
      chairman's committee. But dual share structure remains.
